COPY_TODO — pick a license before public launch.

This file is a placeholder. The boilerplate ships without a chosen
license so the tenant can pick terms that match their business model.
Three common options to consider:

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Option 1: MIT-with-attribution
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Permissive. Anyone can fork, modify, and redistribute, including
commercially, as long as they include the copyright notice.

  - Pros: maximum adoption, easiest to reason about, well understood.
  - Cons: someone could clone your work and compete with you. No
    obligation for forks to contribute back.
  - When to pick: you're treating the boilerplate as a gift to the
    community, or distribution itself isn't your moat.

Use the canonical MIT text from https://choosealicense.com/licenses/mit/
and add your copyright line (e.g. "Copyright (c) 2026 [Your Name]").

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Option 2: Source-available proprietary
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
The code is visible (and tenants can read/modify it for their own
project), but redistribution is prohibited. Common in commercial
boilerplates that bundle ongoing updates or a community.

  - Pros: prevents direct competition; preserves the paid distribution
    channel; tenants still get the transparency of readable source.
  - Cons: incompatible with the open-source ecosystem; requires
    drafting your own license terms or adapting an existing one (BUSL,
    Functional Source License, Elastic License v2, etc.).
  - When to pick: you're selling the boilerplate as a product and
    distribution IS the moat.

Templates worth reading: https://fsl.software (FSL), https://mariadb.com/bsl11/
(BUSL), https://www.elastic.co/licensing/elastic-license (ELv2).

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Option 3: Proprietary EULA
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Closed. The tenant gets a per-seat or per-organization license to use
the code for their own project; no fork/redistribute/sublicense rights.
Strongest commercial protection; requires writing or buying a real EULA.

  - Pros: strongest IP protection; clear commercial terms.
  - Cons: legal cost; tenants can't fork even for their own internal
    fixes; less appealing to developer-tenants.
  - When to pick: you're selling enterprise licenses with named-user
    commitments, or your distribution model needs strong DRM-like
    terms.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

When you've picked, delete this entire file and replace it with the
chosen license text. Don't ship to production with this placeholder
file in place — it provides no legal protection for either you or your
tenants.
